Generating a Dome Tent



One of the best tents for camping within the outdoors may be the dome tent. They're super easy to set up and since the walls are almost vertical there's an additional perception of space.

A dome tent is a freestanding tent, which means once it's set up you can pick it up and move it to a different location without taking it down. Stakes are optional but advisable when it is windy or once the risk of losing the tent when it's amazed by the wind is high.

To pitch a dome tent you must first look for a suitable ground for it. The ground should be flat and free from anything that would certainly be uncomfortable to sleep on. If you have to camp on a slope, make sure you head is on the upside.

To start setting up the dome tent you first lay out the floor tarp after which unfold the tent on top of it. Since it is a freestanding tent you shouldn't have to worry about orientation unless you are going to stake it down.

You can stake the tent down before you decide to setup the poles if it's windy. If so, you have to make sure the tent door is incorporated in the direction that you would like. Once you've aligned the tent the way you like, you can start setting up the poles. Make sure you have the correct number of poles.

To setup the poles you might like to refer to the manual given however in most cases you only need to shake the pole sections to make it snap into position. If you would like the poles to continue for a lot more uses be sure you ease them into place instead of letting them snap.

